  <Fragment slot="hero-subtitle">
    Notion has no built-in dictation. QuickSay adds voice-to-text to every Notion page, database, and comment — with automatic cleanup.
  </Fragment>

  <p class="text-lg">
    Notion is where many teams centralize their knowledge: project docs, meeting notes, wikis, task databases, and personal journals. But Notion has never offered a native dictation feature. If you want to get text into Notion by voice, you need a system-level tool. QuickSay fills that gap by working outside Notion entirely, transcribing your speech and pasting cleaned text into whatever block or field has focus.
  </p>

  <h2 class="font-headline font-semibold text-2xl text-text-primary pt-4">How QuickSay Works with Notion</h2>
  <p>
    Open any Notion page — in the desktop app or in your browser. Click into a text block, a database cell, a comment field, or an inline mention. Hold your QuickSay keyboard shortcut, speak, and release. AI transcription transcribes your speech, AI cleans it into well-structured prose, and the result pastes at your cursor. Because QuickSay works via the clipboard at the system level, there is no Notion integration to install or account to configure.
  </p>

  <h2 class="font-headline font-semibold text-2xl text-text-primary pt-4">Faster Note-Taking for Knowledge Workers</h2>
  <p>
    Knowledge workers use Notion as a second brain — a place to capture ideas, document processes, and organize information. The bottleneck is always input speed. Typing detailed notes interrupts the flow of thinking. Voice dictation removes that friction: think it, speak it, and the cleaned note appears in your Notion page. A paragraph that takes 40 seconds to type arrives in 12 seconds of speaking.
  </p>
